'''Matsuizuka Kofun''' (松井塚古墳) was a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Taishi, Osaka|ja|太子町 (大阪府)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minamikawachi District, Osaka|ja|南河内郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was part of the {{ill|Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|ja|磯長谷古墳群|1=Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|12=draft|12=draft}}. The stone coffin from this kofun has been Historic Site1 as a tangible cultural property by Osaka Prefecture. The Kofun itself no longer exists.

== Overview ==
Matsuizuka Kofun was constructed on the southern slope of a ridge in the Isonokami valley, located at the foot of {{ill|Mount Nijo|ja|二上山 (奈良県・大阪府)|1=Mount Nijō|2=ja|3=二上山 (奈良県・大阪府)|4=ceb|5=Nijō San|6=fr|7=Mont Nijō|12=draft|12=draft}} in southeastern Osaka Prefecture<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. It was discovered in {{ill|1958|ja|昭和33rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} during a well-digging operation at a private residence<ref name="ExplanationBoard">On-site explanation board.</ref>. Later that year, the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education conducted an excavation survey<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>.

The mound’s type is unknown but is presumed to have been square<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. The burial facility consists of a {{ill|Yokoana stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, opening to the south. The chamber construction likely used the {{ill|Tang|ja|唐尺|12=draft|12=draft}} measurement system<ref name="ExplanationBoard"/>. Pebbles were spread across the chamber floor, and atop them was placed a house-shaped sekkaku made of tuff sourced from {{ill|Mount Nijo|ja|二上山 (奈良県・大阪府)|1=Mount Nijō|2=ja|3=二上山 (奈良県・大阪府)|4=ceb|5=Nijō San|6=fr|7=Mont Nijō|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. The sekkaku measures 2.5 meters in length and 1.3 meters in width<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>, and it includes a stone door at the front<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Heibonsha)|1986}}</ref>. The sekkaku had been looted before discovery, but human remains (possibly of two individuals) and fragments of {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft|12=draft}} were recovered<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Heibonsha)|1986}}</ref>.

The kofun is estimated to date to the mid-7th century during the {{ill|Late Kofun period|ja|古墳時代終末期|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. Initially, the site drew attention as a potential {{ill|Baizuka|ja|陪塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (accompanying tomb) of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="ExplanationBoard"/><ref>[http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/kanko_info/rekishi_shiseki/matsuitsukakofun.html Matsuizuka Kofun Sekkaku] (Taishi Town Website).</ref>. The stone chamber’s size also remains significant for studies of burial customs under the {{ill|Taika Retypes|ja|大化改新|12=draft|12=draft}}, as its map_size corresponds to burials of royal status<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Heibonsha)|1986}}</ref><ref name="ExplanationBoard"/>. The kofun is also an important example for understanding the transition of {{ill|Cave Tomb sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The stone coffin was Historic Site1 as an Osaka Prefecture Designated designation1 in {{ill|1973|ja|昭和48th year|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="List"/> and has been relocated and displayed at Taishi Nagomi-no-Hiroba near {{ill|Eifuku-ji|ja|叡福寺|12=draft|12=draft}}.
