'''Matsuizuka Kofun''' (松井塚古墳) was a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] located in [[:en:Taishi, Osaka|Taishi, Osaka]], [[:en:Minamikawachi District, Osaka|Minamikawachi District, Osaka]], [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]]. It was part of the {{ill|Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|ja|磯長谷古墳群|1=Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|qq=}}. The stone coffin from this kofun has been Historic Site1 as a tangible cultural property by Osaka Prefecture. The Kofun itself no longer exists.

== Overview ==
Matsuizuka Kofun was constructed on the southern slope of a ridge in the Isonokami valley, located at the foot of [[:en:Mount Nijō|Mount Nijō]] in southeastern Osaka Prefecture<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. It was discovered in [[:en:1958|Showa 33]][[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]] during a well-digging operation at a private residence<ref name="ExplanationBoard">On-site explanation board.</ref>. Later that year, the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education conducted an excavation survey<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>.

The mound’s type is unknown but is presumed to have been square<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. The burial facility consists of a {{ill|Yokoana stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokoana stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}, opening to the south. The chamber construction likely used the {{ill|Tang|ja|唐尺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tang|qq=}} measurement system<ref name="ExplanationBoard"/>. Pebbles were spread across the chamber floor, and atop them was placed a house-shaped sekkaku made of tuff sourced from [[:en:Mount Nijō|Mount Nijō]]<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. The sekkaku measures 2.5 meters in length and 1.3 meters in width<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>, and it includes a stone door at the front<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Heibonsha)|1986}}</ref>. The sekkaku had been looted before discovery, but human remains (possibly of two individuals) and fragments of [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]] and [[:en:Haji pottery|Haji pottery]] were recovered<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Heibonsha)|1986}}</ref>.

The kofun is estimated to date to the mid-7th century during the {{ill|Late Kofun period|ja|古墳時代終末期|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Late Kofun period|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}</ref>. Initially, the site drew attention as a potential {{ill|Baizuka|ja|陪塚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baizuka|qq=}} (accompanying tomb) of [[:en:Empress Suiko|Empress Suiko]]<ref name="ExplanationBoard"/><ref>[http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/kanko_info/rekishi_shiseki/matsuitsukakofun.html Matsuizuka Kofun Sekkaku] (Taishi Town Website).</ref>. The stone chamber’s size also remains significant for studies of burial customs under the {{ill|Taika Retypes|ja|大化改新|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taika Retypes|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大化の改新|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大化の改新}}, as its map_size corresponds to burials of royal status<ref>{{Harvid|Matsuizuka Kofun (Heibonsha)|1986}}</ref><ref name="ExplanationBoard"/>. The kofun is also an important example for understanding the transition of {{ill|Cave Tomb sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb sekkaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}}.

The stone coffin was Historic Site1 as an Osaka Prefecture Designated designation1 in [[:en:1973|Showa 48]][[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]]<ref name="List"/> and has been relocated and displayed at Taishi Nagomi-no-Hiroba near [[:en:Eifuku-ji|Eifuku-ji]].
